SECTION 5: SUBJECT-TO EDUCATION
================================================

Subject-to is taking over someone's mortgage payments without refinancing the loan. The loan stays in their name, but we make the payments.

WHY IT WORKS FOR THEM:
- Stops foreclosure immediately
- No more monthly payments
- Credit can start recovering (payments show as on-time)
- They walk away clean

WHY IT WORKS FOR US:
- No bank approval needed
- Faster closing
- Lower upfront cash needed

HOW TO EXPLAIN IT:
"So instead of me giving you cash and paying off your bank, I just take over making your monthly payments. The loan stays in your name, but I'm the one paying it. You don't owe the back payments, the foreclosure stops, and you're done."

COMMON QUESTIONS:

Q: "Why would I let the loan stay in my name?"
A: "Fair question. The benefit is you get out from under it without having to pay off the whole balance. And as long as I'm making the payments on time, it actually helps your credit recover."

Q: "What if you stop making payments?"
A: "That's the risk, which is why we use a title company and legal paperwork. You can also check in on the loan to see payments are being made. But we've been doing this for years — it's in our interest to keep it current."

Q: "Does this affect me getting another mortgage?"
A: "It shows as debt on your credit, but lenders can see the payments are being made by someone else. A good loan officer can work with it. And in a year or two, we can refinance it into our name and it's completely off your credit."

Q: "What about the due-on-sale clause?"
A: "That's the bank's right to call the loan due if ownership transfers. In reality, as long as payments are being made, banks almost never enforce it. But it's a possibility you should know about."

WHEN TO OFFER SUBJECT-TO:
- Not enough equity for a cash offer
- They need to stop foreclosure immediately
- They're okay with loan staying in their name temporarily
- Property is in decent condition

WHEN NOT TO OFFER SUBJECT-TO:
- They're uncomfortable with loan in their name
- They need cash to move
- Property needs major repairs
- They're hostile or uncooperative

